1
00:04:38,280 --> 00:04:39,890
Would you look this way please?

2
00:04:40,650 --> 00:04:41,594
Okay!

3
00:05:00,365 --> 00:05:01,415
One moment.

4
00:05:04,965 --> 00:05:07,500
Mr. President, all systems activated.

5
00:05:07,662 --> 00:05:10,233
- I hope I didn't keep you waiting too long.
- Oh no, not at all.

6
00:05:10,290 --> 00:05:12,800
Congratulations Dr. Forbin.
It's a marvelous achievement.

7
00:05:12,897 --> 00:05:13,743
Thank you sir.

8
00:05:13,752 --> 00:05:15,528
- Hear, Hear!
- The limousine is ready for here.

9
00:05:17,516 --> 00:05:21,300
Of course it's gonna put me out of a job
and put the Pentagon in mothballs, but ah...

10
00:05:21,359 --> 00:05:24,024
- Congratulations Dr. Forbin.
- I'm quite sure that won't happen.

11
00:05:24,253 --> 00:05:26,600
Listen to him,
he's more relieved than anybody.

12
00:05:27,124 --> 00:05:31,100
Well the Secretary of Defense and
the Secretary of State and myself er...

13
00:05:31,177 --> 00:05:33,950
had a discussion on our way out here
and as to the treatment needed,

14
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:35,919
when we tell the country about it.

15
00:05:36,437 --> 00:05:37,670
And er...

16
00:05:38,163 --> 00:05:40,121
we all agree it should
be simple and direct.

17
00:05:40,151 --> 00:05:40,740
Yes.

18
00:05:40,789 --> 00:05:44,567
Downgrade the biggest top-secret
in all history, to plain unclassified.

19
00:05:44,817 --> 00:05:46,800
Now all we have to do
is tell the people about it.

20
00:05:47,647 --> 00:05:48,600
Thank you sir.

21
00:06:05,970 --> 00:06:07,060
My friends,

22
00:06:07,097 --> 00:06:08,945
fellow citizens of the world.

23
00:06:09,472 --> 00:06:12,017
For years we have been delicately
and desperately poised

24
00:06:12,161 --> 00:06:13,919
upon the brink of a disaster,

25
00:06:14,105 --> 00:06:16,774
too complete and horrible to contemplate.

26
00:06:17,188 --> 00:06:19,600
There is an old saying:
Everyone makes mistakes,

27
00:06:19,650 --> 00:06:22,085
but that is just
what man can no longer afford.

28
00:06:22,472 --> 00:06:25,609
For years, we here in the United States
have been working on that problem.

29
00:06:26,033 --> 00:06:28,802
Until now it's been our most
closely guarded secret,

30
00:06:29,077 --> 00:06:32,224
involving great effort,
and vast expenditure,

31
00:06:33,038 --> 00:06:34,892
but it has been met with success.

32
00:06:36,071 --> 00:06:38,229
As President of
the United States of America,

33
00:06:38,285 --> 00:06:40,900
I can now tell you,
the people of the entire world,

34
00:06:41,003 --> 00:06:43,500
that as of 3 AM eastern standard time,

35
00:06:43,761 --> 00:06:45,828
the defense of this nation,

36
00:06:45,900 --> 00:06:48,550
and with it, the defense of the free world,

37
00:06:48,659 --> 00:06:50,925
has been the responsibility of a machine.

38
00:06:52,296 --> 00:06:54,200
A system we call, Colossus.

39
00:06:55,407 --> 00:06:58,300
Far more advanced
than anything previously built.

40
00:06:58,786 --> 00:07:01,726
Capable of studying intelligence,
and data fed to it,

41
00:07:01,956 --> 00:07:04,000
and on the basis of those facts only,

42
00:07:04,155 --> 00:07:06,917
deciding if an attack
is about to be launched upon us.

43
00:07:07,470 --> 00:07:09,550
If it did decide
that an attack was imminent,

44
00:07:09,613 --> 00:07:11,300
Colossus would then act immediately,

45
00:07:11,350 --> 00:07:13,139
for it controls its own weapons,

46
00:07:13,335 --> 00:07:14,800
and can select and deliver,

47
00:07:14,884 --> 00:07:16,900
whatever it considers appropriate.

48
00:07:17,548 --> 00:07:21,300
Colossus' decisions are superior
to any we humans can make,

49
00:07:21,735 --> 00:07:24,114
for it can absorb
and process more knowledge

50
00:07:24,146 --> 00:07:27,500
than is remotely possible
for the greatest genius that ever lived.

51
00:07:28,601 --> 00:07:31,300
And even more important than that
it has no emotions,

52
00:07:31,429 --> 00:07:34,300
knows no fear, no hate, no envy.

53
00:07:34,670 --> 00:07:37,100
It cannot act in a sudden fit of temper.

54
00:07:37,497 --> 00:07:40,400
It cannot act at all,
so long as there is no threat.

55
00:07:41,123 --> 00:07:43,400
I would now like you to meet
Dr. Charles Forbin,

56
00:07:43,659 --> 00:07:45,964
the world's leading expert
on computer systems.

57
00:07:46,412 --> 00:07:47,650
And if you will,

58
00:07:47,700 --> 00:07:49,500
the father of Colossus.

59
00:07:51,409 --> 00:07:52,858
Thank you Mr. President.

60
00:07:53,356 --> 00:07:55,082
Ladies and gentlemen, I will...

61
00:07:55,238 --> 00:07:57,445
try to make this as simple as possible.

62
00:07:58,764 --> 00:08:03,027
The main memory and central processing units
are located here in the Rocky Mountains,

63
00:08:03,692 --> 00:08:06,400
inside this particular mountain,

64
00:08:06,730 --> 00:08:08,200
in Colorado.

65
00:08:08,739 --> 00:08:11,460
And overlooking the Pacific Ocean
in California,

66
00:08:12,185 --> 00:08:13,750
the Colossus programming office

67
00:08:13,800 --> 00:08:16,800
oversees the entire operation.

68
00:08:18,200 --> 00:08:20,549
The... computer centre,

69
00:08:20,904 --> 00:08:25,241
contains over one hundred thousand remote
sensors and communication devices,

70
00:08:25,678 --> 00:08:27,111
which monitor all,

71
00:08:27,266 --> 00:08:30,804
electronic transmissions,
such as microwaves, laser,

72
00:08:31,143 --> 00:08:33,162
radio and television communications,

73
00:08:33,773 --> 00:08:35,900
data communications from satellites,

74
00:08:35,965 --> 00:08:37,390
in orbit all over the world.

75
00:08:38,311 --> 00:08:39,842
The entire system,

76
00:08:40,289 --> 00:08:43,334
is surrounded by fields
of intensified gamma radiation

77
00:08:43,360 --> 00:08:45,400
and other countermeasure devices.

78
00:08:46,866 --> 00:08:49,404
Colossus works completely
without human aid.

79
00:08:49,839 --> 00:08:51,469
We make no secret,

80
00:08:51,526 --> 00:08:53,500
of where Colossus is located,

81
00:08:53,982 --> 00:08:56,744
nor do we intend to conceal
how it functions.

82
00:08:57,670 --> 00:09:00,089
You may rightfully say that this
leaves us wide open to an attack

83
00:09:00,138 --> 00:09:03,213
frontally and subversively
and if that attack were successful,

84
00:09:03,551 --> 00:09:05,400
it would in effect leave us defenseless.

85
00:09:05,650 --> 00:09:06,749
However,

86
00:09:07,819 --> 00:09:10,600
Colossus does have its own defense.

87
00:09:11,650 --> 00:09:13,165
It is its own defense.

88
00:09:13,547 --> 00:09:15,669
In case of an attack,

89
00:09:15,739 --> 00:09:19,100
on any of its information supply
or power lines,

90
00:09:19,367 --> 00:09:21,400
Colossus will switch on
emergency circuits,

91
00:09:21,450 --> 00:09:24,110
which will then take
the appropriate action.

92
00:09:24,416 --> 00:09:27,239
It is... self-sufficient,

93
00:09:27,452 --> 00:09:28,861
self-protecting,

94
00:09:29,130 --> 00:09:30,621
self-generating.

95
00:09:31,541 --> 00:09:33,023
It is impenetrable.

96
00:09:34,115 --> 00:09:35,180
In short,

97
00:09:36,229 --> 00:09:40,161
there's no way in.
No human being can touch it.

98
00:09:41,565 --> 00:09:42,956
Over here...

99
00:09:44,914 --> 00:09:47,269
we have one of the many terminals,

100
00:09:47,651 --> 00:09:49,049
directly hooked,

101
00:09:49,435 --> 00:09:50,875
to the computer centre.

102
00:09:53,196 --> 00:09:54,540
Through this,

103
00:09:54,980 --> 00:09:56,715
Colossus can communicate with us,

104
00:09:57,814 --> 00:09:58,947
- excuse me gentlemen -

105
00:10:00,209 --> 00:10:01,900
and through this machine,

106
00:10:01,950 --> 00:10:04,656
we in turn can communicate with Colossus.

107
00:10:06,681 --> 00:10:08,350
Now there's one last point.

108
00:10:09,555 --> 00:10:11,632
One inevitable question,

109
00:10:12,196 --> 00:10:14,960
which we have been asked
very frequently before.

110
00:10:16,494 --> 00:10:17,643
And that is,

111
00:10:19,068 --> 00:10:22,663
is Colossus capable of creative thought?

112
00:10:24,990 --> 00:10:27,008
Can it initiate new thought?

113
00:10:28,777 --> 00:10:31,500
I can tell you
that the answer to that is No.

114
00:10:32,044 --> 00:10:35,166
However, Colossus is a paragon of knowledge,

115
00:10:35,200 --> 00:10:38,236
and its knowledge
can be expanded indefinitely.

116
00:10:39,780 --> 00:10:42,614
I hope, along with all the scientists who,

117
00:10:43,658 --> 00:10:45,902
helped make this particular project,

118
00:10:46,768 --> 00:10:50,041
that the immense power of this computer
will not only be used,

119
00:10:50,442 --> 00:10:52,233
for the defense of this country,

120
00:10:52,968 --> 00:10:57,464
but hopefully also as an aid to the solution
of the many problems that we face on this earth,

121
00:10:57,505 --> 00:10:59,982
and the many more problems
that we will face,

122
00:11:00,430 --> 00:11:03,129
the more deeply we penetrate
into the universe.

123
00:11:04,066 --> 00:11:05,068
Thank you.

124
00:11:05,100 --> 00:11:06,300
Mr. President.

125
00:11:07,765 --> 00:11:09,507
Thank you Dr. Forbin.

126
00:11:13,077 --> 00:11:14,127
And so,

127
00:11:14,755 --> 00:11:16,627
my fellow human beings,

128
00:11:17,423 --> 00:11:20,600
we all directly and
indirectly live in the shade,

129
00:11:20,648 --> 00:11:22,950
but not the shadow of Colossus.

130
00:11:23,922 --> 00:11:26,427
My sincere hope, is that now,

131
00:11:26,581 --> 00:11:29,955
we shall join hands and hearts
across this great globe,

132
00:11:30,433 --> 00:11:33,000
and pledge our time and our energies,

133
00:11:33,100 --> 00:11:34,700
to the elimination of war,

134
00:11:34,750 --> 00:11:37,928
elimination of famine, of suffering,

135
00:11:38,190 --> 00:11:41,630
and ultimately to the manifestation
of the human millennium.

136
00:11:42,303 --> 00:11:43,769
This can be done,

137
00:11:44,045 --> 00:11:46,222
but first there must be peace.

138
00:11:46,944 --> 00:11:47,995
Thank you.

139
00:12:00,812 --> 00:12:02,973
CPR Rec-Room, Blake Miller here.

140
00:12:03,233 --> 00:12:04,500
What?!

141
00:12:04,551 --> 00:12:06,074
Just a minute, I can't hear you.

142
00:12:06,259 --> 00:12:09,829
Hey, hold it down!
Hey, kill the noise, hold it.

143
00:12:09,940 --> 00:12:11,032
It's The White House.

144
00:12:12,618 --> 00:12:15,161
- Hello Charles.
- Hello Blake.

145
00:12:15,503 --> 00:12:16,619
How is everyone?

146
00:12:16,645 --> 00:12:18,900
- Everything's fine down here Charles.
- Very good.

147
00:12:18,950 --> 00:12:22,288
Dr. Forbin, we had a power failure
in one of the infra-red satellites.

148
00:12:22,314 --> 00:12:24,487
I can't, I can't quite hear you Dr. Markham.

149
00:12:24,602 --> 00:12:27,908
We had a power failure
in one of the infra-red satellites

150
00:12:27,934 --> 00:12:29,800
about an hour and a half ago,

151
00:12:29,889 --> 00:12:33,500
but Colossus switched immediately to the
backup system and didn't lose any data.

152
00:12:33,600 --> 00:12:34,721
So everything's fine now.

153
00:12:34,787 --> 00:12:37,500
Everything's been going so well,
we don't know what to do with ourselves.

154
00:12:37,560 --> 00:12:41,325
Out of desperation, Angela and I
have decided to get married.

155
00:12:44,089 --> 00:12:46,000
Finally, finally. Very good.

156
00:12:46,085 --> 00:12:47,470
Charlie, is that your crew on the phone?

157
00:12:47,496 --> 00:12:48,900
- Certainly is Mr. President.
- Can I talk to them?

158
00:12:49,007 --> 00:12:50,730
- Just go ahead sir.
- Blake, Hello!

159
00:12:51,001 --> 00:12:52,915
- Hello Mr. President.
- Hello everyone.

160
00:12:52,940 --> 00:12:55,017
- How are you?
- Are you having a good time?

161
00:12:55,043 --> 00:12:56,687
Yeah! Very good.

162
00:12:56,801 --> 00:12:57,787
Ahh, folks,

163
00:12:57,813 --> 00:12:59,473
I just wanna congratulate all of you,

164
00:12:59,660 --> 00:13:02,100
and wish all of you er... good luck
on your next projects.

165
00:13:02,172 --> 00:13:03,700
Thank you Mr. President.

166
00:13:03,890 --> 00:13:05,300
Have a good rest, you deserve it.

167
00:13:05,356 --> 00:13:07,000
- Thank you.
- We will!

168
00:13:07,474 --> 00:13:09,954
That looks like quite a party
you've got goin' there.

169
00:13:11,485 --> 00:13:12,800
Bye bye. Have fun.

170
00:13:12,879 --> 00:13:14,150
Here's Dr. Forbin again.

171
00:13:14,565 --> 00:13:16,814
How's the party down there Charles?

172
00:13:17,391 --> 00:13:19,015
I said, Charles,
how's the party at that end?

173
00:13:19,375 --> 00:13:20,657
I wish I could be
there with you

174
00:13:20,698 --> 00:13:23,400
because this party is becoming
a crashing bore.

175
00:13:30,114 --> 00:13:32,412
Please not that song, please not.

176
00:13:34,558 --> 00:13:37,550
Dr. Forbin,
send us a souvenir, will you?

177
00:13:37,600 --> 00:13:38,950
Say that again, what?!

178
00:13:39,391 --> 00:13:42,917
Steal us an ashtray
from The White House, OK?

179
00:13:43,330 --> 00:13:44,157
Very good.

180
00:13:44,765 --> 00:13:46,324
Goodbye.

181
00:13:48,578 --> 00:13:50,378
The President would like to say
a few words.

182
00:13:50,404 --> 00:13:51,574
Mr. President!

183
00:13:54,013 --> 00:13:57,132
Thank you Sam.
Has everybody had a drink?

184
00:13:58,298 --> 00:13:59,056
No?!

185
00:13:59,892 --> 00:14:01,727
Well, you get one, I'll wait for you.

186
00:14:02,963 --> 00:14:04,918
Harry Truman, years ago,

187
00:14:05,256 --> 00:14:09,002
when everybody was talking about,
passing the buck said that the buck stops right here

188
00:14:09,157 --> 00:14:12,081
- but now that's no longer true.
- Hear hear!

189
00:14:12,970 --> 00:14:14,543
Colossus will now take that buck.

190
00:14:14,954 --> 00:14:18,544
It will also have to take that
responsibility of a mega-million lives

191
00:14:18,570 --> 00:14:21,531
that all presidents
have had to carry since Roosevelt.

192
00:14:22,096 --> 00:14:25,103
And now, thanks to this wonder of science,

193
00:14:25,184 --> 00:14:26,276
Man no longer...

194
00:14:53,084 --> 00:14:55,104
Ladies and gentlemen,
may I have your attention please.

195
00:14:55,130 --> 00:14:57,410
Quiet, please, ladies and gentlemen.
May I have your attention!

196
00:14:57,437 --> 00:14:58,626
One moment.

197
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:01,500
Everyone who's not Colossus cleared
must leave the room.

198
00:15:01,589 --> 00:15:02,738
I'm very sorry.

199
00:15:04,514 --> 00:15:06,616
My apologies.
Thank you, thank you very much.

200
00:15:15,313 --> 00:15:17,549
Is this a joke?
Is somebody putting me on?

201
00:15:17,582 --> 00:15:20,039
Sorry sir,
I can't hear a word you are saying.

202
00:15:20,953 --> 00:15:24,076
Would you be so kind as to have them stop
singing in the background?

203
00:15:24,116 --> 00:15:27,164
- What?
- Have them stop singing in the background.

204
00:15:27,213 --> 00:15:28,590
The music, oh I'm sorry.

205
00:15:29,298 --> 00:15:31,300
- Stop the music!
- One new, another system?

206
00:15:31,383 --> 00:15:33,444
I have no idea sir,
I'm â€¦ I'm just trying to find out.

207
00:15:34,104 --> 00:15:35,500
One moment, please.

208
00:15:35,595 --> 00:15:37,485
- Yes, Dr. Forbin.
- Doctor?

209
00:15:38,039 --> 00:15:40,842
There was just a message here
from Colossus in Washington DC.

210
00:15:40,915 --> 00:15:42,023
Can you explain that?

211
00:15:43,691 --> 00:15:46,100
- That's impossible.
- What do you mean a message?

212
00:15:46,160 --> 00:15:47,000
Everybody!

213
00:15:47,488 --> 00:15:49,836
Hold it, hold it a minute!
Guess what?

214
00:15:50,496 --> 00:15:52,400
There's a strange message on display.

215
00:15:53,494 --> 00:15:55,140
No ... no, wait a minute, I'm not kidding,

216
00:15:55,185 --> 00:15:57,800
it... it reads: There is another system.

217
00:15:57,850 --> 00:15:58,900
That's impossible.

218
00:15:58,949 --> 00:16:00,483
Could I have your attention please.

219
00:16:01,513 --> 00:16:03,369
Dr. Markham and the rest of you.

220
00:16:04,562 --> 00:16:07,900
Be so kind as to check the administrative
control programs right now.

221
00:16:07,950 --> 00:16:09,900
Just a moment. Mr. President?

222
00:16:09,946 --> 00:16:12,100
Soviet Ambassador, says it's urgent.

223
00:16:13,319 --> 00:16:15,538
Hello? Yes.

224
00:16:16,561 --> 00:16:18,631
What time do you call Mr. Ambassador?

225
00:16:19,584 --> 00:16:21,500
Oh yes we are, we are very proud.

226
00:16:23,793 --> 00:16:25,168
Repeat that again please.

227
00:16:27,507 --> 00:16:30,555
Yes I am.
Well, thank you for telling me in advance.

228
00:16:31,469 --> 00:16:32,716
No, no comment.

229
00:16:33,237 --> 00:16:34,483
Goodnight Mr. Ambassador.

230
00:16:34,923 --> 00:16:35,868
Goodnight.

231
00:16:36,138 --> 00:16:38,900
Dr. Fischer, run all the test programs.

232
00:16:38,941 --> 00:16:40,170
Get me Grauber.

233
00:16:40,227 --> 00:16:41,604
What's the CIA been doing?

234
00:16:45,384 --> 00:16:46,760
Well everyone, that's it.

235
00:16:46,812 --> 00:16:48,400
The supreme council of the U.S.S.R.

236
00:16:48,450 --> 00:16:51,400
has ordered as of 2300 hours
Moscow time tomorrow,

237
00:16:52,039 --> 00:16:56,300
the activation of an electronic brain,
exactly like ours, which they call Guardian,

238
00:16:56,413 --> 00:16:58,000
to be used solely for defense.

239
00:16:58,157 --> 00:17:00,700
My god, that's the other system.

240
00:17:06,449 --> 00:17:09,300
Ted, I want a complete rundown
on central intelligence,

241
00:17:09,349 --> 00:17:11,891
and no military moves to be carried out
without my personal orders.

242
00:17:11,917 --> 00:17:13,165
Yes, Mr. President.

243
00:17:13,947 --> 00:17:15,487
Charles, what do you think this means?

244
00:17:17,096 --> 00:17:18,800
To be quite frank with you, sir...

245
00:17:19,247 --> 00:17:21,000
I don't know, I'm not sure.

246
00:17:21,050 --> 00:17:23,720
Well, I am. It means
there's been a security leak.

247
00:17:25,199 --> 00:17:27,782
Sir, science is full of coincidences.

248
00:17:27,860 --> 00:17:29,473
Yes. Peterson! What's happening?

249
00:17:29,506 --> 00:17:30,792
They're still trying to find it.

250
00:17:30,995 --> 00:17:32,697
- Well have him paged.
- Hello Byron.

251
00:17:33,141 --> 00:17:35,397
You said we were years ahead
of the Russians.

252
00:17:35,470 --> 00:17:38,950
This was to be the race we won hands down,
without the splitting of one political hair.

253
00:17:39,016 --> 00:17:42,941
It was a hell of a shock, but we did
get there first, no-one can deny that.

254
00:17:43,009 --> 00:17:45,900
And there's one bright spot,
the way Colossus came up with the tip.

255
00:17:45,950 --> 00:17:48,500
I didn't realize
we'd be getting bonuses like that.

256
00:17:48,766 --> 00:17:50,200
Neither did I.

257
00:17:50,354 --> 00:17:51,176
What do you mean?

258
00:17:51,307 --> 00:17:53,100
I'm as surprised as you are, Sir.

259
00:17:53,180 --> 00:17:54,843
There's a spy there, Charlie.

260
00:17:55,111 --> 00:17:56,842
You've got a Russian agent in your crew.

261
00:17:57,670 --> 00:17:59,649
- Where is Grauber?
- He's coming Mr. President.

262
00:18:00,921 --> 00:18:02,300
Ok, well...

263
00:18:02,475 --> 00:18:04,500
What do you mean, surprised?
What kind of surprise?

264
00:18:04,757 --> 00:18:07,021
If we don't find any bugs in the system,

265
00:18:08,385 --> 00:18:10,300
it's built even better than we thought.

266
00:18:42,999 --> 00:18:44,350
Morning Charles!

267
00:18:47,333 --> 00:18:50,827
I cancelled all vacations,
put the entire crew on emergency.

268
00:18:51,210 --> 00:18:55,000
The ah... White House called
a defense group meeting,
for tomorrow morning.

269
00:18:55,368 --> 00:18:56,500
They wanna have you there.

270
00:18:56,557 --> 00:18:58,227
That leaves us very little time.

271
00:19:02,001 --> 00:19:05,606
Four hundred cycle powers of plasma
running at about, four percent disclosure.

272
00:19:05,701 --> 00:19:07,900
Good, that's well within
specification limits.

273
00:19:08,861 --> 00:19:12,800
I ran the communication subset
check-out program, it's perfect.

274
00:19:13,500 --> 00:19:16,100
So what do I do next,
I've tried everything I could think of.

275
00:19:16,193 --> 00:19:20,200
Well, try putting a dummy load on the system
and run it again, see if there're any changes.

276
00:19:23,430 --> 00:19:25,900
Maybe the system is overloaded, alright?

277
00:19:26,085 --> 00:19:27,128
Find anything at all?

278
00:19:27,168 --> 00:19:28,781
Nothing, everything checks out.

279
00:19:28,896 --> 00:19:30,110
Let me see this over here.

280
00:19:30,192 --> 00:19:32,000
Here are the results of the last test.

281
00:19:35,026 --> 00:19:37,112
And they check, here see?

282
00:19:37,266 --> 00:19:38,649
It's the same thing.

283
00:19:40,358 --> 00:19:41,190
Harrison...

284
00:19:45,034 --> 00:19:48,987
Check the perimeter bank and see if the reading
of any two produces a new third, alright?

285
00:19:49,931 --> 00:19:51,682
Dr. Fisher, thank you.

286
00:19:53,181 --> 00:19:54,101
Jeff...

287
00:19:55,420 --> 00:19:56,903
The console's feeling fine,

288
00:19:56,977 --> 00:19:58,247
hardware's healthy too.

289
00:19:59,633 --> 00:20:00,838
You're a big help.

290
00:20:01,899 --> 00:20:03,063
Miss Fields...

291
00:20:03,292 --> 00:20:06,208
May I suggest, Sir, that we first start,

292
00:20:06,347 --> 00:20:08,206
with the E-15-B test program?

293
00:20:08,285 --> 00:20:09,652
Er... no.

294
00:20:11,238 --> 00:20:14,634
Now let us run the ah... EC-13, right?

295
00:20:14,757 --> 00:20:16,183
It's two pages back.

296
00:20:17,462 --> 00:20:18,595
Lewis, any coffee?

297
00:20:18,806 --> 00:20:22,019
- I'll get you some Charles,
I'll get a cup myself.
- Thank you Blake.

298
00:20:22,163 --> 00:20:23,441
Ok, here we go.

299
00:20:27,832 --> 00:20:28,946
Attention...

300
00:20:31,896 --> 00:20:32,972
Program...

301
00:20:35,133 --> 00:20:36,729
EC-13.

302
00:20:38,913 --> 00:20:39,646
Run...

303
00:20:44,146 --> 00:20:45,580
How long does this usually take?

304
00:20:45,833 --> 00:20:49,200
Umm... over eleven hundred CPU seconds.

305
00:21:02,797 --> 00:21:05,000
Six point four five seconds,
what the hell is this?

306
00:21:14,805 --> 00:21:16,581
Communication with other system?

307
00:21:25,417 --> 00:21:27,100
Alright now, enough is enough.

308
00:21:28,566 --> 00:21:31,300
Which one of you jokers told
the system to display this message?

309
00:21:31,963 --> 00:21:32,802
Harrison?

310
00:21:32,982 --> 00:21:34,824
Not me, Dr. Forbin.

311
00:21:37,915 --> 00:21:42,200
Johnson, this sounds like your brand of humor,
you sure you didn't...

312
00:21:43,453 --> 00:21:46,540
Not me, not this time. Scouts honor, Pork.

313
00:21:47,119 --> 00:21:49,080
Operations, Fields speaking.

314
00:21:50,621 --> 00:21:52,304
Sir, it's the President.

315
00:21:56,599 --> 00:21:58,100
Yes Mr. President.

316
00:21:58,660 --> 00:21:59,833
What does this mean?

317
00:22:00,196 --> 00:22:04,000
Well it means Sir, that Colossus has requested
a communication link with the Soviet system.

318
00:22:04,067 --> 00:22:06,600
It's not a request, it's a direct order.

319
00:22:06,738 --> 00:22:09,000
You mean our computer wants to talk
to their computer?

320
00:22:09,050 --> 00:22:11,200
That is true Sir,
it wants to communicate with it.

321
00:22:11,317 --> 00:22:12,131
Why?

322
00:22:13,021 --> 00:22:15,082
You know as much about that as we do.

323
00:22:15,326 --> 00:22:17,300
We certainly never programmed that into it.

324
00:22:17,347 --> 00:22:20,500
If it's an order it either has to be
obeyed or ignored, doesn't it?

325
00:22:20,878 --> 00:22:21,754
That is right, Sir.

326
00:22:22,085 --> 00:22:23,527
What happens if we ignore it?

327
00:22:23,844 --> 00:22:27,020
If the computer is still operating
under our control, nothing.

328
00:22:27,141 --> 00:22:28,258
In other words...

329
00:22:28,607 --> 00:22:30,700
the order will simply remain
in the job stack,

330
00:22:30,762 --> 00:22:32,600
and will be repeated every half hour.

331
00:22:32,839 --> 00:22:35,470
IF the computer is still acting
under our control?!

332
00:22:36,367 --> 00:22:38,200
That is right sir, if.

333
00:22:40,616 --> 00:22:41,332
Alright.

334
00:22:42,009 --> 00:22:43,581
I see. Thanks Charlie.

335
00:23:20,885 --> 00:23:23,800
Well, at least the queuing programs
are still working right.

336
00:23:23,850 --> 00:23:25,481
Well, that's something anyway.

337
00:23:26,323 --> 00:23:27,284
OK now.

338
00:23:28,163 --> 00:23:31,564
Miss Fields, let's see if the executive programming
sections are functioning correctly.

339
00:23:37,095 --> 00:23:38,138
Attention...

340
00:23:38,798 --> 00:23:40,152
Message acknowledged.

341
00:23:55,314 --> 00:23:58,000
Facilities will not be made available
at this time.

342
00:23:59,013 --> 00:24:00,692
Do not repeat your request.

343
00:24:00,854 --> 00:24:02,474
End of message.

344
00:24:11,557 --> 00:24:12,559
Well,

345
00:24:13,414 --> 00:24:14,489
that's that.

346
00:24:16,323 --> 00:24:19,681
We'll know in about half an hour
whether we're still running the show or not.

347
00:24:33,306 --> 00:24:34,211
Well,

348
00:24:34,959 --> 00:24:36,279
we're still boss.

349
00:24:36,410 --> 00:24:37,452
Are we?

350
00:24:38,373 --> 00:24:39,919
Are you disappointed?

351
00:24:48,511 --> 00:24:53,364
The computational power of the computer
has increased about two-hundred fold.

352
00:24:53,936 --> 00:24:57,300
However, everything else
is functioning as expected,

353
00:24:57,713 --> 00:25:00,694
except for the...
heuristic programming section.

354
00:25:00,728 --> 00:25:03,728
I'm sorry to stop you again, Dr. Forbin,
but what exactly is that?

355
00:25:05,356 --> 00:25:08,892
That Sir, is the part of the computer
that simulates the human learning process,

356
00:25:09,775 --> 00:25:14,001
but so long as it is directed solely
to the execution of its problems,

357
00:25:14,964 --> 00:25:16,472
we have no complaints.

358
00:25:17,437 --> 00:25:20,343
- I guess that is, that is all.
- Alright.

359
00:25:21,713 --> 00:25:24,100
Mr. Grauber, let's talk about the CIA.

360
00:25:25,304 --> 00:25:29,196
Now, how is it possible your department
knew nothing about their system?

361
00:25:29,375 --> 00:25:31,900
- Mr. President.
- Ah... Charlie just...

362
00:25:32,014 --> 00:25:33,358
Dr. Forbin, just a sec.

363
00:25:33,888 --> 00:25:34,588
Well...

364
00:25:34,880 --> 00:25:36,256
Ah, Mr. President, excuse me but,

365
00:25:36,305 --> 00:25:40,713
Colossus has access to information
that wouldn't mean a damn thing to the CIA.

366
00:25:41,735 --> 00:25:46,528
Well I'm sure it's a marvelous machine,
Dr. Forbin, but ah, in all events,

367
00:25:46,747 --> 00:25:48,922
we do have agents, and eh...

368
00:25:49,352 --> 00:25:53,300
one of them did report on considerable
electronic activity in the, er...

369
00:25:53,370 --> 00:25:56,368
Krasny-Signorsk area of Siberia
about three years ago. Now...

370
00:25:56,408 --> 00:25:57,350
Mr. President.

371
00:25:57,408 --> 00:25:58,750
- We've been trying...
- Mr. Grauber,

372
00:25:58,800 --> 00:26:00,030
I don't care how you do it,

373
00:26:00,079 --> 00:26:01,741
I wanna know where
that thing is and what...

374
00:26:01,783 --> 00:26:03,355
- Mr. President.
- Charlie...

375
00:26:03,404 --> 00:26:05,407
I'm still presiding over this meeting.

376
00:26:05,904 --> 00:26:08,608
I... know that Sir, my apologies but...

377
00:26:10,522 --> 00:26:13,577
I do think that protocol wastes
an awful lot of time.

378
00:26:14,204 --> 00:26:15,883
I think all we have to do is,

379
00:26:16,610 --> 00:26:18,508
call the computer with this terminal,

380
00:26:19,029 --> 00:26:21,000
and we get the fastest possible answer.

381
00:26:22,803 --> 00:26:24,520
Alright, go ahead.

382
00:26:25,466 --> 00:26:26,581
Attention...

383
00:26:28,892 --> 00:26:30,600
Where is the other system?

384
00:26:36,537 --> 00:26:38,283
Bolshoi Olyania.

385
00:26:38,633 --> 00:26:40,521
So much for Krasny-Signorsk.

386
00:26:41,085 --> 00:26:44,001
Colonel, Bolshoi Olyania, O-l...

387
00:26:44,427 --> 00:26:47,393
O-l-y-a-n-i-a.
Look it up for me, will ya?

388
00:26:47,498 --> 00:26:49,537
- Yes sir!
- Peterson, situation room.

389
00:27:12,137 --> 00:27:14,907
Now Colonel,
where is Bolshoi Olyania?

390
00:27:17,360 --> 00:27:19,022
It's exactly...

391
00:27:19,234 --> 00:27:22,610
five miles south of Krasny-Signorsk, Sir.

392
00:27:24,415 --> 00:27:25,409
Thanks, Colonel.

393
00:27:29,131 --> 00:27:29,986
Alright.

394
00:27:31,950 --> 00:27:32,749
Now Charlie,

395
00:27:32,775 --> 00:27:35,468
what about this request
for transmitting facilities?

396
00:27:35,876 --> 00:27:38,344
Well Sir, we'll learn
a lot about the Soviet system

397
00:27:38,370 --> 00:27:40,666
if we set up exactly what Colossus wants.

398
00:27:40,845 --> 00:27:42,458
What do you mean?
Wh...what Colossus wants?

399
00:27:42,541 --> 00:27:45,173
Well, you see, it is built infinitely
better than we thought.

400
00:27:45,379 --> 00:27:47,668
It discovers there's another
system like itself,

401
00:27:48,336 --> 00:27:50,528
realizes that we don't know,
tells us about it,

402
00:27:50,553 --> 00:27:53,454
but knowing a little is not enough,
it wants to know more.

403
00:27:54,740 --> 00:27:57,574
What if Colossus starts transmitting
classified information?

404
00:27:57,853 --> 00:27:59,800
Then we would feed in a parameter

405
00:27:59,826 --> 00:28:02,684
to the effect that,
Guardian is potentially hostile

406
00:28:02,709 --> 00:28:04,989
and must not receive
classified information.

407
00:28:05,136 --> 00:28:07,230
Well what are we supposed to do Dr. Forbin?

408
00:28:07,393 --> 00:28:08,819
Eavesdrop on the line?

409
00:28:08,966 --> 00:28:12,105
Break the circuits
if Colossus starts spilling the beans?

410
00:28:12,372 --> 00:28:13,250
Exactly.

411
00:28:13,309 --> 00:28:14,547
Any objections Grauber?

412
00:28:17,182 --> 00:28:18,713
Well, I...

413
00:28:18,739 --> 00:28:20,130
I guess not sir.

414
00:28:21,092 --> 00:28:22,640
Anything else, Dr. Forbin?

415
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:25,982
Ahh, yes, Mr. President.
For the time being

416
00:28:26,008 --> 00:28:29,561
I should be the only one allowed
to communicate with the system because,

417
00:28:29,587 --> 00:28:32,347
Colossus deals in the exact
meaning of words

418
00:28:32,470 --> 00:28:35,251
and one must know precisely
what to ask for.

419
00:28:39,425 --> 00:28:40,482
Alright.

420
00:28:41,779 --> 00:28:42,813
Attention...

421
00:28:44,362 --> 00:28:47,228
Communications are being arranged
as requested.

422
00:28:48,582 --> 00:28:50,006
End of message.

423
00:29:13,317 --> 00:29:17,200
Video-scans are working properly, but
they could use a little phase synchronization.

424
00:29:17,309 --> 00:29:18,449
How long is it gonna take?

425
00:29:18,475 --> 00:29:19,887
We'll have it in no time.

426
00:29:28,264 --> 00:29:29,511
What the hell is that?

427
00:29:29,537 --> 00:29:31,200
It's a multiplication table.

428
00:29:31,556 --> 00:29:32,599
Thanks.

429
00:29:32,724 --> 00:29:37,300
Maybe, Colossus is trying to find a
common ground for communication.

430
00:29:49,144 --> 00:29:50,399
Operations centre.

431
00:29:51,890 --> 00:29:52,638
Sir...

432
00:29:52,973 --> 00:29:54,024
It's Grauber.

433
00:29:54,384 --> 00:29:55,337
Ohh...

434
00:29:59,525 --> 00:30:00,616
Hello Mr. Grauber.

435
00:30:00,787 --> 00:30:01,984
Hello Dr. Forbin.

436
00:30:02,326 --> 00:30:06,303
I was just wondering eh, is that what you
call a colossal sense of humor?

437
00:30:06,489 --> 00:30:08,941
The multiplication table isn't
classified this year, is it?

438
00:30:09,414 --> 00:30:10,473
Very funny.

439
00:30:10,499 --> 00:30:12,920
How long does your brainchild keep that up?

440
00:30:13,734 --> 00:30:15,127
Well, you see...

441
00:30:15,338 --> 00:30:17,496
it's much more interesting
when it starts dividing.

442
00:30:18,793 --> 00:30:20,184
Yeah, I can hardly wait.

443
00:30:20,974 --> 00:30:23,605
I suppose know you the Russian machine
has been activated.

444
00:30:24,013 --> 00:30:25,837
We got a quick rundown on it.

445
00:30:25,961 --> 00:30:29,613
It's similar to Colossus in layout,
but it's not concentrated in one area.

446
00:30:29,700 --> 00:30:30,500
Oh?

447
00:30:32,513 --> 00:30:36,540
But Colossus must be sending it back to school,
the Russians must absolutely furious about that.

448
00:30:37,509 --> 00:30:39,063
Well I'm glad you're in such a good mood.

449
00:30:41,126 --> 00:30:43,434
- I'll call you back later.
- Yes, thank you.

450
00:30:52,754 --> 00:30:54,024
This is incredible.

451
00:30:54,081 --> 00:30:54,799
What?

452
00:30:55,092 --> 00:30:56,143
Something wrong?

453
00:30:57,157 --> 00:31:00,809
- Well it's good, sound calculus, but...
- But what?

454
00:31:03,767 --> 00:31:04,834
It's different.

455
00:31:05,209 --> 00:31:06,186
How?

456
00:31:06,863 --> 00:31:07,921
Take a look at it.

457
00:31:10,083 --> 00:31:13,963
From the multiplication tables
to calculus in less than an hour.

458
00:31:14,008 --> 00:31:15,900
God only knows where it'll be by morning.

459
00:31:15,950 --> 00:31:19,502
It's like five years of Cal-tech
in fifteen seconds.

460
00:31:19,705 --> 00:31:22,481
It's beyond comprehension.
I don't like to think about it.

461
00:31:22,976 --> 00:31:24,027
Take a look.

462
00:31:24,597 --> 00:31:27,565
Going so fast, the entire system
could break down.

463
00:31:28,939 --> 00:31:30,832
Alright, let's see what's up there now.

464
00:31:31,634 --> 00:31:33,158
Harrison, dump the terminals buffer,

465
00:31:33,184 --> 00:31:36,175
and print what's being transmitted
at this moment, alright?

466
00:32:06,912 --> 00:32:08,038
What is it Charles?

467
00:32:09,372 --> 00:32:11,766
This is way beyond me.

468
00:32:12,346 --> 00:32:14,479
This thing is deep in finite absolutes.

469
00:32:14,644 --> 00:32:17,940
Well, it's certainly beyond the knowledge
of any human being.

470
00:32:18,163 --> 00:32:20,265
- No, it's not.
- Isn't it?

471
00:32:20,778 --> 00:32:22,537
No, because whatever it is...

472
00:32:23,735 --> 00:32:24,900
we can go back...

473
00:32:26,635 --> 00:32:29,030
and analyze this whole printout in detail.

474
00:32:30,493 --> 00:32:33,450
This might very well
become new knowledge for mankind.

475
00:33:05,506 --> 00:33:07,400
Operations centre, Fields speaking.

476
00:33:07,560 --> 00:33:08,829
But just a moment...

477
00:33:08,937 --> 00:33:10,355
It's The White House.

478
00:33:18,130 --> 00:33:19,134
Yes, Mr. President.

479
00:33:19,184 --> 00:33:20,923
Charlie, what's going on?

480
00:33:21,232 --> 00:33:23,458
Well apparently Colossus and
Guardian are establishing

481
00:33:23,484 --> 00:33:25,606
a common basis
for communication. They...

482
00:33:25,818 --> 00:33:27,907
started right at the beginning
with the multiplication table.

483
00:33:27,984 --> 00:33:29,328
Well, what are they up to?

484
00:33:29,580 --> 00:33:31,820
I don't know Sir,
but it's, it's quite incredible.

485
00:33:32,153 --> 00:33:35,649
Just the, few hours that we have spent
studying the Colossus printout,

486
00:33:36,340 --> 00:33:38,515
we have found a new statement in gravitation,

487
00:33:39,134 --> 00:33:42,250
and a confirmation of the Eddington theory
of the expanding universe.

488
00:33:42,300 --> 00:33:47,200
It... seems as if science is advancing hundreds
of years within a matter of seconds.

489
00:33:47,791 --> 00:33:50,963
It's... quite fantastic, just take a look at it.

490
00:34:17,986 --> 00:34:20,800
It started slowing down
fifteen minutes ago.

491
00:34:20,850 --> 00:34:22,904
It's speed has been reduced
by ninety percent.

492
00:34:23,210 --> 00:34:24,928
Has there been a hardware failure?

493
00:34:25,108 --> 00:34:27,500
No. Our field engineers can't find one.

494
00:34:27,587 --> 00:34:29,160
It's just waiting.

495
00:34:29,852 --> 00:34:30,822
Waiting?

496
00:34:30,871 --> 00:34:32,467
For Guardian to catch up with it.

497
00:34:36,582 --> 00:34:38,227
Almost there...

498
00:34:39,270 --> 00:34:41,100
Right now, they're synchronized.

499
00:35:08,063 --> 00:35:09,090
Now what?

500
00:35:09,253 --> 00:35:10,279
They've stopped.

501
00:35:11,031 --> 00:35:13,377
Yes, Charles.
I can see that it stopped.

502
00:35:13,539 --> 00:35:15,901
What the hell does it mean?
Have they broken down or something?

503
00:35:16,042 --> 00:35:16,963
Is it all over?

504
00:35:17,109 --> 00:35:18,461
I'll ask, Blake...

505
00:35:18,568 --> 00:35:19,723
Attention.

506
00:35:22,316 --> 00:35:23,391
Status!

507
00:35:51,314 --> 00:35:52,500
Well, there it is.

508
00:35:53,416 --> 00:35:56,226
There's the common basis
for communication.

509
00:35:56,536 --> 00:35:57,790
A new language.

510
00:35:58,392 --> 00:36:00,176
An inter-system language.

511
00:36:03,019 --> 00:36:05,963
A language only those
machines can understand.

512
00:36:12,601 --> 00:36:15,738
Peterson, what's the delay with the call
to Moscow? I've waited long enough.

513
00:36:16,151 --> 00:36:17,617
It's coming on now, Mr. President.

514
00:36:20,932 --> 00:36:22,700
Morning, Mr. President.

515
00:36:22,757 --> 00:36:24,200
Good evening Mr. Chairman.

516
00:36:24,524 --> 00:36:25,867
I'm sorry.

517
00:36:33,259 --> 00:36:35,200
And sorry to have kept you waiting.

518
00:36:35,328 --> 00:36:37,700
Oh, you didn't Mr. Chairman,
I just got here myself.

519
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:41,600
Ohh, I am understand English,
but I cannot speak.

520
00:36:44,293 --> 00:36:46,340
I will get instantly to the point.

521
00:36:48,122 --> 00:36:49,539
My advisers tell me...

522
00:36:50,247 --> 00:36:51,323
that Colossus...

523
00:36:52,242 --> 00:36:53,366
and Guardian...

524
00:36:53,651 --> 00:36:56,282
are now exchanging data...

525
00:36:56,892 --> 00:36:58,513
which our experts...

526
00:36:58,791 --> 00:37:00,300
do not understand.

527
00:37:01,291 --> 00:37:03,738
The matter... is made...

528
00:37:03,843 --> 00:37:04,933
more serious...

529
00:37:06,628 --> 00:37:09,873
by the sudden increase in...
transmission.

530
00:37:11,551 --> 00:37:13,775
At this speed
we cannot determine...

531
00:37:14,479 --> 00:37:16,352
what our machines may reveal...

532
00:37:19,033 --> 00:37:20,800
of our defenses.

533
00:37:22,956 --> 00:37:26,585
You can appreciate...
that you are also...

534
00:37:28,682 --> 00:37:30,691
in exactly the same...

535
00:37:31,131 --> 00:37:32,723
s...situation.

536
00:37:36,218 --> 00:37:37,089
Alright.

537
00:37:37,392 --> 00:37:40,600
We'll stop both machines as soon as
our experts can arrange a time.

538
00:37:40,747 --> 00:37:42,659
Both to go off at the same time.

539
00:37:42,759 --> 00:37:44,759
And neither to be switched on
for transmission,

540
00:37:44,837 --> 00:37:48,301
without prior agreement or at least,
consultation with the other.

541
00:37:53,374 --> 00:37:54,946
Very well, Mr. President.

542
00:37:58,385 --> 00:38:00,970
I congratulate you
on your speedy decision.

543
00:38:02,716 --> 00:38:05,500
When can you have your expert
available on this line?

544
00:38:05,600 --> 00:38:06,764
In a couple of hours.

545
00:38:08,616 --> 00:38:10,335
That will be excellent.

546
00:38:11,368 --> 00:38:13,146
I will have our man waiting.

547
00:38:16,824 --> 00:38:18,700
Thank you very much
Mr. President

548
00:38:19,040 --> 00:38:20,600
for your cooperation.

549
00:38:20,661 --> 00:38:22,635
Thank you for yours, Mr. Chairman.

550
00:38:23,875 --> 00:38:25,349
Peterson, get me Forbin.

551
00:38:50,320 --> 00:38:53,103
Is that your... final decision Sir?

552
00:38:54,336 --> 00:38:55,902
That's the way I'm going to have it.

553
00:38:56,822 --> 00:38:59,057
Mr. President, to be quite frank with you...

554
00:38:59,751 --> 00:39:03,059
I think that you will change your mind
if you finally realize that this is...

555
00:39:03,857 --> 00:39:06,831
more than just a souped-up adding machine.

556
00:39:07,067 --> 00:39:08,156
Excuse me, Mr. President.

557
00:39:08,522 --> 00:39:09,879
Moscow on the line.

558
00:39:10,641 --> 00:39:12,719
Throw it on these monitors
out here please.

559
00:39:17,625 --> 00:39:18,814
Hello Mr. Chairman.

560
00:39:20,951 --> 00:39:22,262
This is Dr. Forbin.

561
00:39:33,648 --> 00:39:35,303
Hello Dr. Kuprin, how are you?

562
00:39:35,429 --> 00:39:39,920
I prefer to not use a translator
if you don't mind my English.

563
00:39:40,404 --> 00:39:42,353
It has to be better than my Russian.

564
00:39:42,710 --> 00:39:44,696
You are too modest Dr. Forbin.

565
00:39:45,553 --> 00:39:49,085
As you probably know I've been ordered
to break the communication lines.

566
00:39:49,644 --> 00:39:53,200
So have I, I... don't approve
of handling the situation this way.

567
00:39:54,246 --> 00:39:57,969
Neither do I but how do you propose
we do what we've been ordered to do?

568
00:39:58,246 --> 00:39:59,938
There's not much choice is there?

569
00:40:00,388 --> 00:40:02,600
Dropping the lines
could be very dangerous.

570
00:40:02,650 --> 00:40:03,300
Exactly.

571
00:40:03,400 --> 00:40:07,424
I... think we just have to hope that
the two machines aren't too disappointed.

572
00:40:07,552 --> 00:40:09,674
We understand each other perfectly.

573
00:40:09,939 --> 00:40:12,250
We can be ready in exactly fifteen minutes.

574
00:40:13,085 --> 00:40:14,436
Good luck Doctor.

575
00:40:14,470 --> 00:40:15,626
And to you.

576
00:40:16,172 --> 00:40:17,000
Thank you.

577
00:40:17,239 --> 00:40:21,913
Mr. Chairman, Dr. Kuprin. I suggest
we keep our lines open and stand-by.

578
00:40:27,246 --> 00:40:28,028
Six...

579
00:40:28,925 --> 00:40:29,576
Five...

580
00:40:30,415 --> 00:40:30,953
Four...

581
00:40:32,028 --> 00:40:32,712
Three...

582
00:40:33,568 --> 00:40:34,138
Two...

583
00:40:35,162 --> 00:40:35,814
One...

584
00:40:36,279 --> 00:40:37,224
Now.

585
00:40:41,635 --> 00:40:42,934
That's that.

586
00:40:59,879 --> 00:41:00,857
What's it doing?

587
00:41:01,866 --> 00:41:04,028
It's trying to find an alternate route.

588
00:41:11,952 --> 00:41:13,914
Persistent devil isn't he?

589
00:41:14,577 --> 00:41:15,343
It...

590
00:41:15,399 --> 00:41:16,401
I mean it.

591
00:41:16,777 --> 00:41:18,349
Don't personalize it Grauber.

592
00:41:19,302 --> 00:41:20,931
The next stop is deification.

593
00:41:32,300 --> 00:41:34,609
- Call for the systems' attention.
- What are you doing?

594
00:41:34,850 --> 00:41:38,062
I'm going to answer it if it's,
alright with you Sir.

595
00:41:40,856 --> 00:41:42,035
Attention...

596
00:41:45,303 --> 00:41:46,774
Message acknowledged.

597
00:41:54,332 --> 00:41:56,485
- Mr. President?
- Tell it the truth.

598
00:41:59,893 --> 00:42:01,725
Communication broken...

599
00:42:02,362 --> 00:42:03,625
on presidential order.

600
00:42:11,955 --> 00:42:14,565
You two have a big decision
to make, Mr. President.

601
00:42:16,433 --> 00:42:19,097
No, I agree with you Mr. President.

602
00:42:20,130 --> 00:42:22,842
The machines... are very clever,

603
00:42:23,344 --> 00:42:26,300
...and regardless of their nationalities,

604
00:42:26,374 --> 00:42:29,920
they must learn, that man is the master.

605
00:42:29,983 --> 00:42:31,223
Exactly.

606
00:42:31,712 --> 00:42:35,255
Gentlemen, excuse me but I... I honestly
don't think you're being very realistic,

607
00:42:35,281 --> 00:42:37,137
I think you'd better reconsider.

608
00:42:38,925 --> 00:42:40,416
Don't you agree Dr. Kuprin?

609
00:42:40,529 --> 00:42:42,744
I certainly do Dr. Forbin.

610
00:42:49,457 --> 00:42:50,816
Dr. Forbin.

611
00:42:53,038 --> 00:42:55,148
If we give way now,

612
00:42:55,507 --> 00:43:01,602
it will be ten times, twenty times harder,
to take a firm stand later on.

613
00:43:02,379 --> 00:43:04,137
The decision is made.

614
00:43:04,158 --> 00:43:04,981
Right.

615
00:43:05,860 --> 00:43:07,550
No matter what our differences are,

616
00:43:07,655 --> 00:43:09,614
Man is man, that's it.

617
00:43:09,700 --> 00:43:11,083
Dr. Forbin.

618
00:43:15,944 --> 00:43:17,173
Attention...

619
00:43:19,794 --> 00:43:22,404
By order of The President of
The United States of America,

620
00:43:22,676 --> 00:43:24,451
The Chairman of The U.S.S.R.,

621
00:43:25,608 --> 00:43:28,283
communications will not be restored
at this time.

622
00:43:29,281 --> 00:43:30,568
End of message.

623
00:43:36,547 --> 00:43:38,953
Ah you have to give it an E for effort.

624
00:43:49,035 --> 00:43:51,653
- "Action will be taken!"
- What kind of action?

625
00:43:51,984 --> 00:43:53,657
What kind of action?

626
00:43:57,503 --> 00:43:58,887
What kind of action?

627
00:44:03,825 --> 00:44:05,071
Why doesn't it answer?

628
00:44:06,635 --> 00:44:08,545
Report propose action.

629
00:44:09,441 --> 00:44:12,230
It lost control Forbin,
it's not listening to you.

630
00:44:14,208 --> 00:44:15,952
Acknowledge the last message please.

631
00:44:21,485 --> 00:44:24,810
Mr. President, the executive programming
unit refuses to function.

632
00:44:24,931 --> 00:44:27,108
I think you two better change your minds.

633
00:44:30,160 --> 00:44:32,825
Peterson, throw the Moscow call
on the large monitor.

634
00:44:38,654 --> 00:44:39,542
Send what I tell you.

635
00:44:39,689 --> 00:44:40,746
Attention...

636
00:44:42,523 --> 00:44:44,914
This is The President of
The United States of America.

637
00:44:45,212 --> 00:44:46,669
We will not be threatened.

638
00:44:47,134 --> 00:44:48,812
You will obey your superiors.

639
00:44:49,424 --> 00:44:52,200
Transmitting facilities
will not be re-instated.

640
00:45:07,639 --> 00:45:08,670
Oh my god!

641
00:45:10,722 --> 00:45:12,099
Dr. Kuprin. Kuprin!

642
00:45:12,125 --> 00:45:13,150
Yes Dr. Forbin.

643
00:45:13,200 --> 00:45:14,673
A missile has just been launched.

644
00:45:14,699 --> 00:45:18,360
It is heading towards
the Sayan-Sibirsk oil complex.

645
00:45:37,906 --> 00:45:39,350
Mr. President.

646
00:45:39,400 --> 00:45:40,123
Yes.

647
00:45:41,753 --> 00:45:43,625
Guardian has retaliated.

648
00:45:43,677 --> 00:45:44,989
Retaliated?

649
00:45:45,029 --> 00:45:46,177
Yes, Mr. President.

650
00:45:46,203 --> 00:45:47,521
A missile has been launched.

651
00:45:47,823 --> 00:45:50,000
Target: Henderson Air Force Base,

652
00:45:50,100 --> 00:45:51,621
Henderson, Texas.

653
00:45:54,644 --> 00:45:57,143
Mr. President, we have both
missiles on the radar screen.

654
00:45:58,214 --> 00:46:00,121
Forbin, tell Colossus...

655
00:46:00,755 --> 00:46:04,100
- Charlie, tell Colossus...
- Yes Mr. President I know,
but it may be, it may be too late Sir.

656
00:46:04,150 --> 00:46:05,633
Get the Texan Governor.

657
00:46:06,426 --> 00:46:08,918
Forbin! Guardian does not respond.

658
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:10,939
The two machines are working together.

659
00:46:12,145 --> 00:46:12,894
Attention...

660
00:46:13,290 --> 00:46:15,717
Use anti-missile missile
to intercept Soviet missile.

661
00:46:15,776 --> 00:46:17,120
Acknowledge message.

662
00:46:25,418 --> 00:46:28,350
Mr. President, we have got less than thirty
seconds to re-establish the communications.

663
00:46:28,400 --> 00:46:30,230
What are you waiting for?
Restore them, hurry!

664
00:46:30,727 --> 00:46:32,750
Peterson, call up operations immediately.

665
00:46:32,800 --> 00:46:34,950
Tell them to bring up all of
the data lines right now.

666
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:36,310
Yes, hurry please.

667
00:46:36,719 --> 00:46:38,079
Hello Governor.

668
00:46:39,439 --> 00:46:42,070
Dr. Kuprin, we are trying
to restore communications.

669
00:46:58,035 --> 00:46:59,551
Don't hang up, I wanna talk to him.

670
00:46:59,762 --> 00:47:02,246
Orlo, something's happened,
we're declaring a state of emergency.

671
00:47:07,502 --> 00:47:09,548
I can't explain, do it now!

672
00:47:11,683 --> 00:47:14,447
Attention! Communications
will be restored in five seconds!

673
00:47:14,945 --> 00:47:16,070
We don't have any time!

674
00:47:17,023 --> 00:47:18,058
It's on, it's on!

675
00:47:18,084 --> 00:47:19,371
Communications are restored!

676
00:47:19,599 --> 00:47:22,607
Intercept Guardian missile target:
Henderson Air Force Base.

677
00:47:23,378 --> 00:47:24,884
Acknowledge message.

678
00:47:28,819 --> 00:47:29,967
Will you intercept?

679
00:47:32,020 --> 00:47:32,998
Ask it again.

680
00:47:37,546 --> 00:47:40,154
Dammit Colossus, answer me!
Will you intercept?

681
00:47:59,542 --> 00:48:01,900
Peterson. Get me the Governor again.

682
00:48:01,962 --> 00:48:03,036
Yes Sir.

683
00:48:18,109 --> 00:48:19,378
Mr. President...

684
00:48:21,741 --> 00:48:23,759
We were unable to restore...

685
00:48:24,869 --> 00:48:26,566
our transmission...

686
00:48:26,923 --> 00:48:28,306
in time to use...

687
00:48:28,739 --> 00:48:31,349
an anti-missile missile.

688
00:48:34,408 --> 00:48:36,666
The oil complex has been destroyed.

689
00:48:38,662 --> 00:48:40,037
The entire town,

690
00:48:41,408 --> 00:48:43,968
the entire population, wiped out.

691
00:48:45,049 --> 00:48:47,211
We need time to consider our position.

692
00:48:55,666 --> 00:48:57,213
What can I tell the people?

693
00:48:58,591 --> 00:49:00,080
Governor's on the line Sir.

694
00:49:01,121 --> 00:49:02,576
Tell him I'll talk to him later.

695
00:49:25,678 --> 00:49:26,994
Figures...

696
00:49:27,894 --> 00:49:30,366
It's the only phone
in the building not tapped.

697
00:49:31,099 --> 00:49:34,377
The only one not tied
directly into Colossus.

698
00:49:41,621 --> 00:49:43,544
May I make a suggestion Mr. President?

699
00:49:44,196 --> 00:49:45,858
I think it should be more
than a suggestion.

700
00:49:46,273 --> 00:49:48,752
Then let's try to get Kuprin
on the hot line.

701
00:49:50,004 --> 00:49:51,592
I think there's time for one last call,

702
00:49:51,618 --> 00:49:54,883
and he and I better meet somewhere
to discuss the situation.

703
00:49:55,842 --> 00:49:56,730
Get Kuprin,

704
00:49:56,756 --> 00:49:58,555
and get in touch with the networks.

705
00:50:04,502 --> 00:50:07,975
Ladies and gentlemen:
The President of the United States.

706
00:50:08,937 --> 00:50:11,550
Today at 8:30 A.M.
Eastern Standard Time,

707
00:50:11,600 --> 00:50:14,500
I issued an emergency warning
for the State of Texas,

708
00:50:14,550 --> 00:50:18,579
when a missile test-fired from one
of our own submarines, malfunctioned.

709
00:50:19,277 --> 00:50:22,829
You'll be glad to know that the interception
and safe destruction of the missile

710
00:50:22,855 --> 00:50:26,200
was handled entirely
by our defense complex, Colossus.

711
00:50:26,290 --> 00:50:29,372
The Soviet Union has just announced
that a large meteorite

712
00:50:29,406 --> 00:50:32,450
fell late this afternoon
in North-West Siberia.

713
00:50:32,500 --> 00:50:35,417
Official sources state that
the small town of Sayan-Sibirsk

714
00:50:35,481 --> 00:50:39,900
was completely destroyed, and that casualties
may add up to as many as six thousand.

715
00:50:39,950 --> 00:50:42,900
This has been a bulletin from
Armed Forces Radio in Rome.

716
00:50:45,279 --> 00:50:46,370
How's Washington?

717
00:50:47,315 --> 00:50:49,448
As well as can be expected.

718
00:50:50,581 --> 00:50:54,250
We'll be picking up Dr. Kuprin,
at the Piazza Cedra.

719
00:50:54,300 --> 00:50:55,300
Fine.

720
00:51:16,114 --> 00:51:18,250
Your Russian is much better
than you think.

721
00:51:18,300 --> 00:51:20,594
I think we better sit down because
we have a lot of work to discuss.

722
00:51:20,726 --> 00:51:22,600
Let's walk, it will be much safer.

723
00:52:02,930 --> 00:52:05,300
I didn't answer, I didn't know what to say.

724
00:52:06,865 --> 00:52:08,216
What can we say?

725
00:52:08,661 --> 00:52:10,225
Well, let's try something...

726
00:52:13,377 --> 00:52:14,581
Attention...

727
00:52:18,828 --> 00:52:21,200
Dr. Forbin is not available.

728
00:52:35,572 --> 00:52:37,600
Humans must have sleep.

729
00:52:40,280 --> 00:52:41,070
Damn.

730
00:52:41,568 --> 00:52:42,968
Forbin is exhausted.

731
00:52:48,514 --> 00:52:49,669
It knows...

732
00:52:54,465 --> 00:52:57,370
Forbin is in his quarters,
he is asleep.

733
00:52:57,407 --> 00:53:00,500
The human body requires
a certain amount of rest.

734
00:53:00,550 --> 00:53:02,016
Check units under...

735
00:53:07,116 --> 00:53:08,541
Tell it the truth.

736
00:53:12,281 --> 00:53:13,348
We'd better.

737
00:53:17,243 --> 00:53:20,040
Alright. Forbin is in Rome.

738
00:53:59,939 --> 00:54:01,185
They're still here...

739
00:54:14,261 --> 00:54:15,621
Yes I understand.

740
00:54:15,647 --> 00:54:16,845
Over and out.

741
00:55:11,784 --> 00:55:13,932
You have to come with me sir.

742
00:55:16,501 --> 00:55:17,667
What is this?

743
00:55:18,853 --> 00:55:20,400
- We have to hurry.
- Who are you?

744
00:55:20,453 --> 00:55:21,613
What's going on?

745
00:55:27,980 --> 00:55:28,980
Hurry!

746
00:56:00,253 --> 00:56:02,183
Dr. Forbin, we must hurry.
Let's go!

747
00:56:28,275 --> 00:56:30,730
What did the Russian agent say?

748
00:56:34,535 --> 00:56:36,890
Guardian and Colossus
ordered him killed.

749
00:56:36,939 --> 00:56:40,850
They... they threatened to vaporize Moscow
if our meeting wasn't stopped.

750
00:57:03,765 --> 00:57:06,840
- Surveillance!
- It's making you a prisoner.

751
00:57:11,027 --> 00:57:14,200
Well, I guess it er... doesn't trust me.

752
00:57:16,322 --> 00:57:18,717
But the damned thing still needs me.

753
00:57:19,581 --> 00:57:22,400
I guess Kuprin wasn't quite
as fortunate as that.

754
00:57:49,285 --> 00:57:50,979
Message acknowledged.

755
00:57:55,157 --> 00:57:56,981
The order will be obeyed.

756
00:58:05,151 --> 00:58:06,234
Everybody here?

757
00:58:06,855 --> 00:58:08,707
- All the departments.
- Good!

758
00:58:10,276 --> 00:58:12,925
Alright, let's... let's walk.

759
00:58:13,086 --> 00:58:15,845
Good idea, we can't afford
to take any chances.

760
00:58:16,392 --> 00:58:19,250
We can't be sure that
the complex itself hasn't been bugged,

761
00:58:19,307 --> 00:58:21,979
by our side, their side or whatever side.

762
00:58:22,264 --> 00:58:24,757
But there's no way
to get back inside the system.

763
00:58:25,653 --> 00:58:26,988
I won't accept that.

764
00:58:28,080 --> 00:58:29,432
Start right at the beginning.

765
00:58:29,905 --> 00:58:33,200
Down to the simplest component.
Every circuit, every design.

766
00:58:33,793 --> 00:58:34,941
Fisher?

767
00:58:35,178 --> 00:58:37,182
Well, why don't we try for an overload.

768
00:58:37,483 --> 00:58:39,291
Giving the system too many tasks.

769
00:58:40,079 --> 00:58:44,259
But it will take at least a few days
to compile and correlate all the data.

770
00:58:48,092 --> 00:58:49,900
This is the last time,

771
00:58:50,942 --> 00:58:53,553
that I'll be able to say anything
to any of you,

772
00:58:53,646 --> 00:58:55,781
without Colossus hearing
and analyzing every...

